1. COLLECT RAW DATA
   Download weather CSV files for each year from 2020 to 2026.
   Each file contains hourly meteorological observations for hundreds of European cities.
   Variables available : temperature, rain, wind speed, wind direction, humidity, clouds, snow, visibility.

2. DATA CLEANING
   Filter the dataset to keep only the 20 cities required by the competition.
   Set the visibility column to 0 — it is 100% NaN and useless for the model.
   Parse timestamps to UTC and sort by city and time.
   Remove duplicate rows on the (city_name, timestamp) key.
   Apply physical clipping based on real European weather records (WMO, Météo-France, Copernicus) :
   temperature in [-45, 50], wind in [0, 75], rain in [0, 200], humidity in [0, 100].
   Impute remaining NaN values per city using a cascade strategy :
   linear interpolation for internal gaps, forward fill for trailing gaps, backward fill for leading gaps,
   and global median as a last resort.
   Extract hour and month from the timestamp for seasonal features.
   Export one clean CSV file per year : weather_{year}_clean.csv.

3. FEATURE ENGINEERING
   Build a structured feature vector phi(X) of dimension 98 from the raw tensor X of shape (20, 24, 8).

   Block 1 — Current values : extract the last observed state of Paris across all 8 variables.
   Block 2 — Windowed statistics : compute mean and std over 6h and 24h windows for temperature, wind, rain, humidity and clouds.
   Block 3 — Temporal lags : compute differences between current and past values at lags 1, 2, 3, 6, 12 and 23 hours.
   Block 4 — Geographic weighting : weight neighboring cities by inverse distance w_i = 1 / (1 + d_i / median(d)).
              Compute weighted averages and spread between Paris and its neighbors.
   Block 5 — Wind decomposition : convert wind speed and direction into cartesian components u = W sin(theta), v = W cos(theta).
   Block 6 — Thermal advection : project neighbor wind vectors onto the direction toward Paris and weight by temperature difference.
   Block 7 — Wind acceleration : compute discrete second derivative of wind speed to capture inertia.
   Block 8 — Spatial Laplacian : approximate thermal diffusion using (T_neighbor - T_Paris) / distance^2.
   Block 9 — Wind convergence : measure directional coherence of neighboring winds using circular mean resultant length.

4. DELTA DECOMPOSITION
   Instead of predicting the absolute future value y_{t+6} directly,
   train the model to predict the variation delta_y = y_{t+6} - y_t.
   Reconstruct the final prediction as y_hat = y_t + delta_y_hat.
   This reduces target variance since sigma_delta^2 = 2 * sigma_y^2 * (1 - rho_6) << sigma_y^2,
   which improves convergence and signal-to-noise ratio.
   Rain is predicted directly (not as a delta) because its distribution is zero-inflated
   and the delta is not informative.

5. MODEL TRAINING
   Train three independent HistGradientBoostingRegressor models, one per target variable.
   Temperature and wind use Huber or absolute error loss, robust to meteorological outliers.
   Rain uses absolute error loss adapted to its zero-inflated distribution.
   Training data : 2020–2025 (approximately 52,000 samples).
   Validation data : 2026 (approximately 8,000 samples), strictly separated in time to avoid data leakage.

6. HYPERPARAMETER OPTIMIZATION WITH OPTUNA
   Use Optuna with the TPE (Tree-structured Parzen Estimator) sampler to search the hyperparameter space.
   Parameters explored : loss function, learning rate, max iterations, max leaf nodes, min samples per leaf, L2 regularization, max bins.
   Each trial is evaluated on the 2026 validation set using mean absolute error.
   Run 50 to 100 trials per model to find the optimal configuration.

7. FINAL RETRAINING
   Once the best hyperparameters are identified, retrain each model on the full dataset 2020–2026.
   This enriches the training set with the most recent data before deployment.

8. MODEL EXPORT
   Serialize the three trained models using pickle :
   model_temp.pkl, model_wind.pkl, model_rain.pkl.
   These files are uploaded directly to ML Arena alongside agent.py.

9. AGENT DEPLOYMENT
   The agent loads the three pkl files at initialization.
   At each prediction step, it builds the 98-dimensional feature vector from the input tensor X,
   runs the three models to predict the deltas,
   reconstructs the absolute values and clips wind and rain to be non-negative.
   Final score achieved on ML Arena : L = -0.28, competitive at leaderboard level.
